Every year a number of people's health goes down after a flu or a car accident or any stress that triggers it. I think trying to get your TSH down to one or less by using a mix of T3 and T4 is a good idea and then like Memantine and Piracetam are brain drugs that are safe to try.

Neurology is the weirdest part of medicine because you can map out exactly which part of the brain was affected by a stroke by making the patient like recite a poem backwards while waving with his left hand and and then it's "ok what do we do now" and the answer is nothing really

I always roll my eyes a bit when people who shill various supplements go like "this is X substance, it helps with: - digestion, - headaches, - mood issues, - sleep quality, - depression", because biology is so general that childhood asthma medication works against senile dementia

Windows which show only the sky, but not buildings, ground, hills in distance, etc. make any room feel like a prison. Like the window is high up on the wall and you just see a square of blue sky and clouds passing and nothing else. Makes you feel like an animal trapped in a hole.

This hospital room has one single small window from which I just see a tiny piece of skyscape. Like a glass of deep sea water. I am the Mayan priest in a hole with the jaguar in the cell next to me and a door is opened from which water and meat are lowered down to us to feast on.
No that's my job sorta, other people are the hospitalized ones

Soaking a piece of bread into grease feels like a very primordial human act. Can imagine soldiers on wartime rations scrubbing the bottom of their plates with a slice of stale bread to get the little droplets of melted chicken fat and butter left there after eating their meals.

I'm always impressed by people who are able to sense solar storms and cool solar weather astrology type stuff like that and e.g. get a headache or another interesting symptom, because someone can probably break a wooden chair over my head and I still wouldn't even notice anything

Memories of love, happiness, family, etc. can be far more painful than memories of sorrow and ruin if they remind you of someone you lost. The only memories that never turn painful are ones of survival: running away from dogs, hiding in a bush, falling down a mountain and living.

No one thinks back with bitterness at the night he survived wrapped in wet clothes in the cold outside by drinking brandy to warm his freezing hands or regrets swimming out of a current dragging him into the sea. Crude survival is thrilling, even the memory of it invigorates us.
